SIMPLE: emerald
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Emerald
<hw>Em"er*ald</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>emeraude</ets>, OF. <ets>esmeraude</ets>, <ets>esmeralde</ets>, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧meraude</ets>, L. <ets>smaragdus</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/; cf.
<?/kr. <ets>marakata</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A
precious stone of a rich green color, a variety of beryl. See
<er>Beryl</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>A kind of type, in size between
minion and nonpareil. It is used by English printers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note> ⟦hand⟧ This line is printed in the type called
<xex>emerald</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Emerald</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Emerald
<hw>Em"er*ald</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of a rich green color, like that
of the emerald.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Emerald</xex> meadows.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Byron.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Emerald fish</b></col> <fld>(Zo⟦oum⟧l.)</fld>, <cd>a fish
of the Gulf of Mexico (<spn>Gobionellus oceanicus</spn>), remarkable for
the brilliant green and blue color of the base of the tongue; -- whence
the name; -- called also <altname>esmeralda</altname>.</cd> --
<col><b>Emerald green</b></col>, <cd>a very durable pigment, of a vivid
light green color, made from the arseniate of copper; green bice;
Scheele's green; -- also used adjectively; <as>as, <ex>emerald
green</ex> crystals</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>Emerald Isle</b></col>, <cd>a
name given to Ireland on account of the brightness of its verdure.</cd>
-- <mcol><col><b>Emerald spodumene</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Lithia
emerald</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Min.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Hiddenite</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Emerald nickel</b></col>.
<fld>(Min.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Zaratite</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Emeraldine</ent>⟦br⟧
